snippet.textDisplay: From what I could see, I actually preferred Taran's video and agree 100% with Niko. From a technical aspect, his video was an absolute masterpiece in what could be seen. iJustine's video reminded me of a streamer who overuses wacky sound effects and 20+ scenes. It was cluttered and ridiculous with overly flamboyant scene transitions. Taran seems that he is the type of person that criticizes himself to insane levels, so much so that he hampers himself, he's afraid to take risks.  iJustine on the other hand is the JJ Abrams of YouTube in that she overdoes the editing (e.g. lens flares) to the point of undoing the quality of the video. An editor should hone the vision of the video, not think they have a better way of doing it. In a couple more years Taran will be an unrivaled master of editing.

snippet.textDisplay:
This program ultimately makes me wonder what would happen if we brought Justine, Taran, and many other High Profile YouTubers to edit programming such as News Articles for WGBH's Greater Boston (I997) or even Uncut Video Game Commentaries akin to the ones that you see by Joshua Adams (BikdipOnABus), Jamie Clement of Clement's Corner (ClementJ64), BrainScratch Commentaries, The Super Gaming Brothers, or even my own works on Royameadow: The Channel, I would totally want to see how they would handle editing a program in a formula that they have virtually no experience with and make it look and/or feel like a masterpiece.
Unlike Justine or Taran, I primarily develop my material in MAGIX Vegas Pro (Version 0I6 Only; used to edit with Versions 0II to 0I4 for the longest time, but thanks to my new lighting/shading HDR engine uniQue Vision, I have retired the PurLight Engine that I had been using in Version 0I4, so that build is deprecated for use on my end), and my editing style mostly falls within the Television Broadcast, Late Night Talk Show, Uncut Commentary, Video Magazine, and 200X Decade DVD Video Promotion formulas, among others, which allows for me to have a very firm allowance in variety with my choices of editing and production quality; due to the fact that I would be using resources such as Twixtor to up the footage into 060 Frames per Second and media assets such as Station IDs, Broadcast Watermarks in the Lower Left or Lower Right Corner, One to Five Minute Commercial Breaks, and Sidebar Wallpapers for handling material in the 04:03, 05:04, 08:07, or 0I:0I Aspect Ratio, you would get a dynamically different experience when compared to what we've seen today and when you compare Broadcast Quality to Web Video Quality for the editing, you truly are given a very different level of judging: If I were part of that panel with Faruk, Niko, Jenna, and Kyle, they would be able to understand what would work and not work for the Austin Evans Example Program if this were done for Television and not an online platform such as Facebook, Twitter, or YouTube; this is why I feel that many YouTubers have still not made it to Broadcast Television because the demand is different on that front and thus the production would require massive amounts of changes, which is why I am happy that I have stuck with my Early '70s to 200I WGBH~style editing formula with hints of the modern trends that have come from the 200X DVD Era and even 20II to 20I9 YouTube, it allows for viewers to have a feel that resembles local public television while not feeling that they're having the done to death Video Blog/Vlog format shoved down their throats, we need to see more people using the editing choices of those from the I97X to Early 200X decade or else what we see nowadays will become far too simplistic, flat, plastic, and uninspired, which is not what I want going into 202X, Professional Grade Video Production is only as tricky as the editor makes it and it requires having a vast knowledge of plentiful ends of the industry to truly get the practice optimized, that case is proven here and it's part of why Justine and Taran did not get a single 09 or 0I0 by the panel, in my view.
